6) Rename the experience level columns as below.¶

SE  Senior Level/Expert
MI  Medium Level/Intermediate
EN  Entry Level
EX  Executive Level
In [17]:
for indexes,row in df1.iterrows():
    if df1["experience_level"][indexes]=="SE":
        df1["experience_level"][indexes]="Senior Level/Expert"
    elif df1["experience_level"][indexes]=="MI":
        df1["experience_level"][indexes]="Medium Level/Intermediate"
    elif df1["experience_level"][indexes]=="EN":
        df1["experience_level"][indexes]="Entry Level"
    elif df1["experience_level"][indexes]=="EX":
        df1["experience_level"][indexes]="Executive Level"
df1

Data Exploration¶

1) Write a python program to find out top 15 jobs. Make a bar graph of sales as well.¶

In [21]:
top_jobs = df1['job_title'].value_counts().head(15)
plt.rcParams['font.size'] = '35'
font={
    'size':100
}
body_font={
    'size':50
}
plt.figure(figsize=(135, 35))
plt.bar(top_jobs.index,top_jobs.values,width=0.5,color="darkred")
plt.ylim(0,1100)
plt.xlabel("Job Title",fontdict=body_font)
plt.ylabel("Number of People",fontdict=body_font)
plt.title("Top 15 Jobs",fontdict=font)
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

2) Which job has the highest salaries? Illustrate with bar graph.¶

In [22]:
best_pay_jobs = df1.groupby('job_title')['salary_in_usd'].mean().sort_values(ascending=False).head(5)
font={
    'size':50
}
body_font={
    'size':25
}
plt.rcParams['font.size'] = '15'
plt.figure(figsize=(30, 30))
plt.bar(best_pay_jobs.index,best_pay_jobs.values,width=0.3,color=['midnightblue','mediumblue','blue','mediumslateblue','violet'])
plt.xlabel("Job Title",fontdict=body_font)
plt.ylabel("Average Salaries",fontdict=body_font)
plt.title("Top 5 higest paying jobs",fontdict=font)
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

3) Write a python program to find out salaries based on experience level. Illustrate it through bar graph.¶

In [23]:
salaries_experience = df1.groupby('experience_level')['salary_in_usd'].mean()
plt.rcParams['font.size'] = '15'
font={
    'size':50
}
body_font={
    'size':25
}
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 15))
plt.bar(salaries_experience.index,salaries_experience.values,width=0.2,color=['seagreen','limegreen','green','darkgreen'])
plt.xlabel("Experience Level",fontdict=body_font)
plt.ylabel("Average Salaries",fontdict=body_font)
plt.title("Salaries according to experience",fontdict=font)
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

4) Write a Python program to show histogram and box plot of any chosen different variables. Use proper labels in the graph.¶

4.1) Histogram¶

In [24]:
plt.rcParams['font.size'] = '20'
font={
    'size':50
}
body_font={
    'size':25
}
plt.figure(figsize=(20, 20))
plt.hist(df1['experience_level'],color='silver',bins=25)
plt.xlabel("Experience Level",fontdict=body_font)
plt.ylabel("Number of workers",fontdict=body_font)
plt.title("Number of workers according to experience level",fontdict=font)
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()
